Q: How to use the C socket API in C++ on z/OS A: <p>You'll find quite often that a feature that you want to use is guarded by a &quot;feature test macro.&quot;</p>
<p>The best way to know is to keep a copy of the IBM manuals handy:</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/CBCPG1A0/CCONTENTS?DT=20090606065305" rel="nofollow noreferrer"> z/OS V1R11.0 XL C/C++ Programming Guide</a></li>
<li><a href="http://publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/EDCLB1A0/CCONTENTS?DT=20090607203246" rel="nofollow noreferrer"> z/OS V1R11.0 XL C/C++ Run-Time Library Reference</a></li>
</ul>
<p>The IBM publications are generally very good, but you need to get used to their format, as well as knowing where to look for an answer.</p>
<p>You should ask your friendly system programmer to install the [XL C/C++ Run-Time Library Reference: Man Pages
] on your system.  Then you can do things like &quot;man connect&quot; to pull up the man page for the socket connect() API.  When I do that, this is what I see:</p>
<p>FORMAT</p>
<p>X/Open</p>
<pre><code>#define _XOPEN_SOURCE_EXTENDED 1
#include &lt;sys/socket.h&gt;

int connect(int socket, const struct sockaddr *address, socklen_t address_len);
</code></pre>
<p>Berkeley Sockets</p>
<pre><code>#define _OE_SOCKETS
#include &lt;sys/types.h&gt;
#include &lt;sys/socket.h&gt;

int connect(int socket, struct sockaddr *address, int address_len);
</code></pre>
<p>So the answer is, select which socket format you wish to use, and then add the <code>#define</code> that corresponds to your choice.</p>

Q: How to replace Quill default link tooltip with a custom Angular component in ngx-quill? A: <p>t's hacky, but you have to override the show function of the snow theme:</p>
<pre><code>javascript
let that = this;
this.quill.theme.tooltip.show = function(){
  that.quill.formatText( this.linkRange.index, this.linkRange.length, 'link', 'URL HERE' );
}
</code></pre>
<p><a href="https://stackoverflow.com/questions/45800805/override-quill-editor-link-with-angular-2/48030242#48030242">[1]</a></p>
<p>This shows that overriding the Snow theme tooltip behaviour (its <code>show</code>/<code>hide</code>/<code>edit</code> methods) is the place Quill decides to display the built‑in popup — replacing or disabling that is necessary if you want a fully custom UI.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>For those having problems in Angular:</p>
<pre><code>js
    QuillModule.forRoot({
      modules: {
        toolbar: [
          [{ header: [false, 1, 2] }],
          [&quot;bold&quot;, &quot;italic&quot;, &quot;underline&quot;],
          [&quot;blockquote&quot;],
          ['link', 'image', 'video'],
          ['clean']
        ],
      },
      bounds: &quot;document.body&quot;,
      theme: &quot;snow&quot;
    })

</code></pre>
<p>The link maybe hidden in Angular, and changing the bounds here does not work because of the way Angular is generated. However, this will fix it:</p>
<pre><code>html
&lt;quill-editor bounds=&quot;self&quot;&gt;

</code></pre>
</blockquote>
<p><a href="https://stackoverflow.com/questions/38924971/quill-link-tooltip-is-invisible-by-default/61298869#61298869">[2]</a></p>
<p>Quill positions the tooltip relative to its configured bounds; in Angular you frequently need to control bounds or render your popup into body to avoid clipping/Z‑index issues.</p>
<hr />
<h3>Short guidance (concrete, actionable)</h3>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Disable or replace the Snow tooltip</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Override or monkey‑patch the theme tooltip methods (e.g., <code>quill.theme.tooltip.show/hide/edit</code>) so Quill does not open its native tooltip when the toolbar link button or link in content is clicked. Your toolbar handler alone may not stop theme code from showing the tooltip — override it.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Render your Angular component into document.body and position it</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><p>Rendering into <code>document.body</code> is fine (prevents clipping). After creating the component view, compute the toolbar icon position and place the popup accordingly:</p>
<ul>
<li><p><code>const rect = linkButton.getBoundingClientRect();</code></p>
</li>
<li><p>Position popup with <code>left/top</code> using <code>rect</code> plus page scroll (use <code>window.scrollX/scrollY</code>), and optionally respect editor/bounds.</p>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><p>Ensure popup has high z-index and <code>position: absolute</code> so it appears over the editor.</p>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Replace/extend the Quill Link blot so formats read/write your attributes</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><p>To have <code>quill.getFormat(range)</code> return your custom attributes, implement the blot methods Quill expects. Example pattern (minimal, adapt names):</p>
<pre><code>typescript
const BaseLink = Quill.import('formats/link');

export class CustomLink extends BaseLink {
  static blotName = 'link'; // register as 'link' to *replace* default link behaviour
  static tagName = 'A';

  static formats(domNode: HTMLElement) {
    const formats: any = {};
    const href = domNode.getAttribute('href');
    if (href) formats.href = href;
    const custom = domNode.getAttribute('data-myattr');
    if (custom) formats.myattr = custom;
    return formats;
  }

  format(name: string, value: any) {
    if (name === 'myattr') {
      if (value) this.domNode.setAttribute('data-myattr', value);
      else this.domNode.removeAttribute('data-myattr');
    } else {
      super.format(name, value);
    }
  }
}

Quill.register(CustomLink, true);

</code></pre>
</li>
<li><p>Important: register it to override the built‑in link format (use <code>blotName = 'link'</code> or register to <code>'formats/link'</code>) so Quill's <code>getFormat</code> will surface your attributes.</p>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<hr />
<h3>Tips &amp; Alternatives</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>Use the toolbar handler to open your form, but still override the theme tooltip — the handler alone doesn't suppress the native tooltip.</p>
</li>
<li><p>When editing an existing link, get the link's format via <code>quill.getFormat(range)</code> after you override/replace the link blot; your <code>formats()</code> implementation must extract all data-attributes from the DOM node.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Add event listeners to hide the popup on editor scroll/resize/blur; remove/restore the theme methods on destroy.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<hr />
<h3>Next Steps (what to try now)</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>Override <code>quill.theme.tooltip.show</code>/<code>edit</code> to noop or to call your open‑popup logic instead of the built‑in UI.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Implement <code>static formats(domNode)</code> and <code>format()</code> in your CustomLink blot and register it as the <code>link</code> format.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Create the Angular component dynamically attached to <code>document.body</code>, compute position from <code>button.getBoundingClientRect()</code>, set <code>style.left/top</code> with page scroll offsets, and show it.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Test <code>quill.getFormat(range)</code> after registering the custom blot — it should include your custom attributes.</p>
</li>
</ul>
